WHATS YOUR FAVORITE COLOR?
____________________________________
It’s probably in Grenada! This is St Georges, it”s colorful capital! Definitely my favorite town in the Caribbean, and probably my favorite island too!

HAVE YOU EVER BEEN TO THE CARIBBEAN?
____________________________________
If you have been following along my Stories the last few weeks you might have seen me island hopping in the Caribbean! It was my first time in the region, and Im visiting every country from South to North! Have you been to the Caribbean? Whats your favorite spot?
____________________________________
I’ll be sharing my favorite spots and moments in the upcoming series, like this sunset in St Lucia during our stay at the @marigotbayresort.

@WANDERREDS LIST OF ALTERNATIVE 7 WORLD WONDERS:
____________________________________
+ Meroe Pyramids, Sudan.
+ Tiger’s Nest, Bhutan.
+ Lalibela rock-hewn churches, Ethiopia.
+ Bagan Pagodas, Myanmar.
+ El Djem Colliseum, Tunisia.
+ Christ the Redeemer, East Timor.
+ Tikal Mayan Ruins, Guatemala.

Definitely not as famous as their ‘older’ siblings, maybe not as beautiful, but surely less crowded!
____________________________________
What underrated man-made Wonder would make your list?

WHERE ARE YOU FROM? I’M 🇪🇸.
____________________________________
The Edge of the World, Saudi Arabia. Never would have thought Saudi had such insane views, would you?

SAUDI ARABIA: the best kept secret in the Middle East.
____________________________________
This Middle Eastern giant had been closed up for tourism since it’s foundation. Just recently, with the new 2030 vision introduced by Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman, they’ve starting issuing special e-visas for sports and cultural events. I was one of the few first tourists to visit, this past December, for the Formula E Race held in Riyadh, the capital. Currently, there is another Sharek event taking place: the Italian Supercup! With a Sharek e-visa, you are granted 30 day access to anywhere in the country, with no restrictions!
____________________________________
This has been a major game changer in the race to visit every country, since traditionally, Saudi visas were one of the 3 hardest to come by! Now, just visit www.sharek.sa and stay tuned for the next event!____________________________________
Recent or past politics aside, Saudi Arabia is an exciting destination with a variety of landscapes and people! Hope to be back soon, since I loved my time there last month!
____________________________________
Feel free to drop your questions in the comments if you have any! Dont forget to tell me which picture was your favorite too!

WHY DO I LOOK SYRIAN?
____________________________________
Walking the streets of Damascus, and even in my later visits to Saudi and Sudan, everyone thought I was Syrian! There is a historic explanation for this:
____________________________________
The Umayyad Caliphate, an arabic empire with capital in Damascus, extended all the way to Al-Andalus, or Spain in the early 8th century. They remained in the Iberian Peninsula well over 700 years and hence, stayed, mixed and blended with the local population and culture. Religion might’ve not stuck, but looks surely did! 😂✌️

OLD vs NEW?
____________________________________
Many people argue that Sheik Zayed Mosque in Abu Dhabi is the most beautiful one in the World. However, I’m fascinated by historic ones, like this Umayyad Mosque in Damascus. Newly erected buildings have little appeal for me, whereas old gems that stood the pass of time captivate me. Inside and out, this Mosque is gorgeous, holds the tombs of St John the Baptist and Salah Adin, and even still has traces of its past as a Church and previously, a Roman temple.
____________________________________
How about you? What do you prefer, new or old?

MY THOUGHTS AFTER MY TRIP TO SYRIA:
____________________________________
1. Most places in the country are now safe to visit, namely Damascus, the capital.
2. Locals are eager to go back to a ‘normalized living’, after the struggles of being in a war-zone not more than 7 months before.
3. This ancient city, one of the oldest inhabited places in the World, still conserves all of its historic beauty, value and charm. The same can’t be said for other parts of the country, like the ruins in Palmyra (sacked, damaged and spoilt during the War, and now filled with mines).
4. Every single person I met was welcoming, warm and helpful. Their broken English and my raunchy 10 words in Arabic were no obstacle in our communication. Smiles, signs, its all you need to understand if you really want to. Syrians know this. One of the most approachable I’ve met. Possibly what they’ve been through has fostered this eager to please and welcome the first visitors in years.
5. Media fails to, once again, capture the positives of countries that have suffered horrors. Politics aside, it’s important to shine light to some of the green stems that rise amongst the shadows. *PLEASE GUYS, don’t believe a biased one-sided view of conflicts. Travel to defeat bigotism and narrow-mindedness.
**Disclaimer: Do your homework, ask and listen to what other experienced travelers that have recently visited have to say. Stay in touch with local agents, visit with a reputable tour if you aren’t ready to do it solo. But, NEVER STAY HOME if you want to see it for yourself.

WHAT ARE YOUR NEW YEAR’s RESOLUTIONS?
____________________________________
Here are mine:

1. FINISH
2. ALL
3. 59
4. COUNTRIES
5. I
6. HAVE

THANK YOU ALL FOR THIS EPIC 2018!!
____________________________________
This Sudanese sunset behind the ancient Nubian city of Meroe was probably one of the best in 2018. It’s been a Year of achievements, visiting 39 new countries and repeating visits to another 7. That’s more than last Year, but hopefully less than the next. 2018 was the Year of my leap, when I quitted my job and pursued full-time my goal of being the youngest Spaniard to visit every country. Its also the Year Instagram became my #1 source of income and allowed to cover all my travel expenses. Something I couldn’t have imagined a while back. I owe that to all of you following along my journey and supporting with your likes & comments in my posts, day in & day out (even when I pick the wrong picture to post 😂). Hope you get all you set out to achieve next Year! One thing is certain: you will always have me in your corner!💪😎

WHAT ARE YOUR PACKING TIPS?
____________________________________
Here are some of mine:

1. TRAVEL LIGHT! If you are just going to use something just once or twice, leave it at home. Always question everything you are putting in your bag/suitcase!

2. Bring multipurpose stuff! A sweater can serve as pillow, a towel can be a blanket... 3. Prepare for the cold with several warm layers that you can easily combine depending on the temperature.

4.  Roll up your clothes so that they don’t wrinkle!

5. Always pack based on when you’ll need it! The sooner, the handier everything should be!

6. Use packing cubes like these from @ebagsonline! They neatly and easily allow you pack your suitcase quickly, from anywhere, even the Villa’s Pool!

Consider this my application to replace Daniel Craig as the first Spanish James Bond.

WHAT’s YOUR FAVORITE BEACH DESTINATION?
____________________________________
They say grass is always greener, and I guess in Fiji oceans are always bluer!
____________________________________
If you have been following my Stories, you’ve probably seen I’m having the best time in Maldives! No worries, my first post from country 133 will come soon! I needed some days to fully enjoy it, get the creative juices flowing, and get shooting & editing!
____________________________________
So, this will be my last post from the Pacific in a while! I chose Fiji, probably my favorite destination from my 3 months out there. And one of the best beach destinations I’ve been to, second to, maybe Maldives?
WHERE DOES YOUR ROAD LEAD? WHATS YOUR BIGGEST GOAL OR DREAM?
Roadtrips were invented by a Kiwi, that’s a fact.

HOW FAR IN ADVANCE DO YOU PLAN YOUR TRAVELS?
____________________________________
After my last posts’ discussion where I shared that I plan my trips very far ahead, I received many questions and DMs regarding planning. Booking holidays in advance will save you tons of money, especially if you travel on high season! The downside is that you cant leave much room to spontaneous adventures.
____________________________________
For me, Im just a bit more conscious nowadays that I really need to fine tune the logistics of visiting the bunch of countries that I have left! I try to cover every region altogether, so that I avoid having to go back and visit any leftover countries! Some connections are not as evident as it would seem, for ie: Saudi to Sudan is only $100! Arguably the cheapest flight into Khartoum! So, get researching and planning guys!

WHERE ARE YOU TRAVELING NEXT?
____________________________________
As you know, I have 65 countries left, and a loose intention to finish by 2019. I’ve mapped out more or less my calendar for next Year’s travels, and its going to be the most epic one yet! But lets not get ahead of ourselves, and take it one country at a time.
____________________________________
For me November will be in: Maldives, Paraguay, Uruguay and Buenos Aires (Argentina). And December will take me back to Lebanon, to visit Syria, and from there to Saudi Arabia and Sudan, right before Xmas at home!

WHAT’S BEEN YOUR BEST RECKLESS DECISION WHILE TRAVELING?
____________________________________
It was a Thursday in Samoa, my 4th day in the island, and despite it being quite cloudy and forecasts giving a 80% chance of rain, I decided to rent a scooter and explore. 20min into my cross country trip, rain started to pour down. My initial reaction was to turn around and give in to the tropical storms. I stopped, realized that it was my last chance to explore Samoa, and that some water wouldn’t stop me from it. I ended up driving around for 6hours, was lucky enough to catch a break and take a few shots, but most importantly, enjoyed crossing the villages, seeing kids play touch rugby and getting to know the rural side of Samoa. Yes, I was completely drenched and soaked from head to toe, and eventually had to throw away my clothes (thats why I always take rags on my trips), but boy was it worth it. DISCLAIMER: I drove around super slow! Roads formed pools easily and had quite a few potholes. Im all about adventure, but drive carefully if you are ever renting scooters on an island!
I 💙U

I just noticed my feed is slowly turning just orange and blue. Went to the Doctor and he prescribed green for my next post. Hopefully it’ll cure this South Pacific Fever.
____________________________________
Bay of Islands was simply delightful to drive around. These coastal roads should definitely make it into your itineraries for NZ North Island!

node.text:
ARE YOU DOING ENOUGH TO SAVE OUR PLANET?
____________________________________
Visiting the Pacific nations has been very eye-opening for me in terms of ecological awareness. Countries like Kiribati (first picture) or Tuvalu (second) are made up of tiny atolls. Here, despite how idyllic their beaches might seem, you’ll find tons of plastic waste all over. If you swipe right, you’ll see the dumpsite north of Funafuti, where rubbish is just piled up and covered with sand. This however, is not the single biggest problem these countries face: climate change and the rise of oceans. At only 2 meters above sea level and with recessing reefs, the risk of being swallowed up by the ocean is bigger than ever. So much, that despite foreign aid’s efforts to build up walls, a plan B to reallocate these communities in bigger islands like Fiji or NZ is already in place.

DO YOU PREFER STAYING AT A LOCAL HOMESTAY OR A LUXURY HOTEL?
____________________________________
Luxury hotels have above and beyond all the comforts you might need in your holidays or on the road. However, there is just something special about modest accomodations: experiencing the daily live of locals first hand, unplug from the stresses of our routines, and well, amazing value!
____________________________________
While I love working with hotels all over the World, it’s always refreshing to find a ‘local home away from home’. For me, balance is key! How about you?
____________________________________
There’s no right or wrong answer, just depends on your circumstances and style of travel!

WHATS YOUR “DRUG” OF CHOICE?
____________________________________
Most recently, mine has probably got to be diving. I love the floating sensation and freedom you have when exploring the underworld!
____________________________________
Have you dove before? Do you have any hobbies or passions you are addicted to at the moment?____________________________________
Leaving to Tuvalu today for a few days, wifi is scarce there, so might be MIA for a while! I’ll catch up with all your comments and DMs as soon as I come back team! 🚀🚀
@divers_den

WHAT THREE THINGS WOULD YOU TAKE TO A DESERTED ISLAND?
____________________________________
Having been to a few almost deserted islands in these past weeks in the Pacific, I can know fully comprehend the hardships of being stranded in one of these idyllic atolls for days. These would be my 3 picks and why:

1. A DRONE WITH EXTRA BATTERIES: pictures from the beach with your camera or phone just wont be the same, and you need the occasional distraction. 
2. PHONE WITH TONS OF EBOOKS: download all those universal novels you’ve always wanted to read! You’ll never have more time on your hands! 
3. EXTERNAL BATTERY: at least 20.000 mah to juice up your toys and keep you busy for a few days! There is no electricity to charge anything, so its essential. No worries, there isnt any wifi or cell coverage either, so your phone’s battery will last miraculously longer!

WHY DO I VISIT EVERY COUNTRY?
____________________________________
I get asked this question all the time. The simple answer is that no two countries are the same, and every single one is unique in its own way and has something interesting to offer.
____________________________________
Take Nauru, arguably one of the least visited countries in the World, an 21km2 island, with a small population of 10.000. My weekend visit to this charming country was full of some of the best sunsets I’ve ever seen and the getting to know incredibly friendly people in the toughest situation I’ve ever witnessed.
____________________________________
Australia has a refugee camp in the island for all immigrants that try to reach their coasts by boat. You heard that right: boat! Escaping from tough conditions in their nations of origin, many times seeking asylum, they endure months long oceanic journeys to reach a safe haven in Australia. However, they are never allowed to set foot Down Under and are taken to Nauru, where most have been held for 5 years waiting for their applications to be processed.
____________________________________
The problem is very complex to just cover it in a brief caption. However, these heroes (allow me that liberty) I met in Nauru, were one of the friendliest human beings I have seen on the road. Foad from Baghdad, Akorn from Suleymaniye and MD from Isfahan, I wish you a quick resolution to your situation, and that you may finally have your freedom back! Being so positive and driven as you are, you will thrive, Im sure of it.
____________________________________
To many people, visiting certain countries with no apparent touristic appeal does not much sense. While I respect that, for me, those are the countries I enjoy the most!

WHAT NATURAL WONDER DO YOU WANT TO SEE MOST?
____________________________________
One of the major highlights of our trip to Australia was to finally get to visit the Great Barrier Reef. Giving the declining state of corals and reefs everywhere in the World, unfortunately it has become a now or never situation unless we can change and be more environmentally responsible.
____________________________________
With it, I’m 4/7 in the official List of 7 Natural Wonders of the World: ✅ Everest
✅ Victoria Falls
✅ Grand Canyon
✅ Great Barrier Reef
🔥 Pão de Azucar in Rio
🔥 Northern Lights
🔥 Paricutin volcano

____________________________________
Huge thanks to @divers_den for making it possible!

WHATS YOUR NEXT DESTINATION?
____________________________________
Staring at these cotton candy skies in @portdouglasdaintree, waiting for a sign on where I should head next. 
____________________________________
South and Central America before the end of the Year? Iran in Nowruz? West Africa in Feb? Slowly but surely, will be resolving my calendar for the upcoming months! You’ll be the first to know! ✌️😜

ARE YOUR SUMMER HOLIDAYS OVER?
____________________________________
Good luck to all of you going back to the office/school after the end of the Summer. I kinda miss it... NOT! 🙈
____________________________________
Since quitting my job in late May, Ive spent all Summer abroad, except two weeks! Still a little over 4 weeks for me to go! Bring on Vanuatu, Fiji, Tuvalu, Tonga, Samoa & NZ!

DO YOU THINK PEOPLE CAN CHANGE? 
____________________________________
It’s one of the biggest questions I pose myself on my travels.
____________________________________
I used to believe people at a certain age had their personality and they were not able to change it. Now, Im certain new life experiences, goals, purposes, and ultimately being out of your comfort zone exposed to changes, can definitely be a catalyst for changing people’s mindsets, views and even personalities! Do you agree?

DO YOU SNORKEL OR DIVE?
____________________________________
I love doing both, and find them to be incredible experiences in their own way! 
____________________________________
Palau is certainly a haven for both, with abundance of marine life. It is there that I encountered one of the most epic species I’ve seen underwater: GIANT CLAMS! 
____________________________________
Whats the most interesting ocean life you’ve seen?

WHATS YOUR FAVORITE ISLAND?
____________________________________
Palau was an interesting discovery! Although beauty seems hard to find once you land in the airport and walk around Koror city, the whole thing completely changes as you change your perspective. 
____________________________________
From the air, it looks like Heaven on Earth, and well, from below the sea, it’s just hard to compete with its diving and snorkeling wonders!
____________________________________
Used Mavic Air & @polarpro filters.

ARE YOU A SLOW OR A FAST TRAVELER?
____________________________________
The eternal debate. It’s almost like a Civil War, whenever you meet other travelers and discuss your itineraries for that same destination. 
____________________________________
Always limited by time & money, travelers plan their adventures according to their interests and personalities. So, there’s no one single universal better way to travel that applies for all of us (sure, indefinite time with indefinite money, forever traveling... 😂✌️).
____________________________________
There are those who prefer to stay longer in fewer places, vs those who rather cover more in less time. Slow travelers usually have the higher moral ground, defending a more in-depth exploration of destinations. However, Im quite certain that our personalities have a lot to do with it too! Fast travelers usually wake up earlier, and go to bed later. They probably cover the same things, just in a more intense itinerary, with barely any down time.
____________________________________
Im personally a fast traveler nowadays, I’d rather see 3 cities instead of 1, see as much as I can. But I feel like it may also vary depending on the trip, your mood, the destination...
____________________________________
Whatever the case, I strongly believe that any shape of traveling is better than not traveling. Whatever your way is, JUST GO!

WHICH PLACE WOULD YOU GO BACK TO?
____________________________________
I’ve you’ve followed me for a while you know I don’t get to go back to many places. My number one travel goal is to visit every country, so all my resources (time & money) are focused on that direction. 
____________________________________
Still, my list of places I want to go back to keeps getting longer! Lebanon is the latest addition to that list. First, because its an amazing country full of life and joy, as well as a cultural crossroad second to none. But also, because as you know, I fell sick for the better part of my stay there, and even had to fly back home to recover. Those things happen when you are on the road so much, and it’s just another reason to go back! 
____________________________________
Special thanks to @legraybeirut for taking such good care of me! Especially Rita, their Marketing Manager, who personally drove me to the pharmacy to get my meds! Lebanese hospitality for you! Really happy the hotel was perfectly located and I could see the sights in Beirut before heading home. 🙏😊

HOW MANY COUNTRIES ARE THERE?
____________________________________
It’s one of the most common questions I get every day whenever someone learns Im visiting every country. Truth is, there is no definitive answer! There are many lists going around, but no general consensus. I will give you the criteria I follow and the reasons behind it.
____________________________________
To answer the question, we should first consider answering another: What makes a country a country? A few theories suggest some factors: a defined territory, a constant population, a government and the ability to establish relations with other nations. However the most widely accepted notion in international law establishes the need to be RECOGNISED as such by other states.
____________________________________
Therefore, the most accepted country count would be 193 countries, the members of the UN. However, I and a few others, include 4 other countries: Palestine, Taiwan, Kosovo and Holy See. These are either UN observers or at least recognised by many UN nations. Thats why, I consider I need to visit 197 countries for my quest to be complete! 
____________________________________
These shots were taken in Transnistria. A de facto country in Moldova that has its own government, borders...but is not recognised by any UN member. Our visit was very interesting and I 100% recommend it to anyone around Chisinau. Its an easy day trip and you will find many soviet and Russian memorabilia everywhere!

IF YOU COULD TRAVEL BACK IN TIME, WHICH AGE WOULD YOU PICK?
____________________________________
Asmara, the capital city of Eritrea definitely has that feel of being transported not just to a different place, but to a different moment in time altogether. 
____________________________________
Old Italian bars with their espresso machines from the 60s still up and running, auto repair shops to fix those old vehicles that drive up and down the city streets, and my favorite: bike shops that can mend any two wheeler in a jiffy! 
____________________________________
I loved my time in this city, as a tourist, it doesnt get better than these unique places.

WHAT DOES TRAVEL TEACH YOU?
____________________________________
My short trip to Kurdistan Region, in Iraq, taught me many things.
____________________________________
First and foremost, that we shouldnt feel sorry for our daily problems. Surely they aren’t worth the worry, and definitely don’t affect my overall VERY fortunate situation: Im healthy, Im surrounded by loved ones, and are free to roam and choose my future. Many people out there arent that lucky. In Iraq, their lives have been shaken to the ground in the last few years and put to the hardest test there is. And they still manage to be happy and prosper, looking at the positive side of life.
____________________________________
The second thing I learned was that media is usually wrong. (Like all the time, big time). They exagerate reality and even draw a cartoonish view of life in certain countries. The parts of Iraq I saw, felt safe and stable. 
____________________________________
Third, my rules of what makes a country a country were also put to a test. This deserves a specific post later on, but being from a country that suffers from nationalist independentists,  Kurdistan Region’s case of 97% Independence approval and their de facto self-government made a strong case against my own political beliefs. Though Im not comparing it to Spain, where acceptance is very far from that figure, its hard to argue against the freedom of the people to decide.
____________________________________
Last but not least, the kindness of the people in the Middle East continues to impress me on every trip. Hama & Younes showed me around their beautiful homeland and I couldnt be more thankful for it!

____________________________________

____________________________________
Mine: Faroes (or Iceland), Australia (or California) and Japan (or Hong Kong).
____________________________________

I’VE QUIT MY JOB! (Read til end).
____________________________________
This is probably the hardest post caption I’ve had to write since I started @wanderreds a few years back. I’ve gone over it a few times in these last days, trying to be as clear as possible with you guys with the decision I’ve made.
____________________________________
Throughout this time on Instagram, my slogan has always been “travel to every country in the World, while still working from 9 to 5”. I will have visited 113 countries until then, and I’m still an advocate on the possibility of balancing personal life, travels and your professional career. That hasn’t changed. 
____________________________________
During this time, I’ve been ultimately very committed to the goal of actually visiting every country in the World. Not as a distant finish line down the road of an uncertain future, but every day working hard to get closer to it and really achieve it. It has come to a point where, if I have any chance at completing this life goal of visiting every country, I should do it right now, without hesitation. We all evolve, priorities change, family comes into play, and I may not have a chance to do it in the distant future. 
____________________________________
In this decision, I’ve also factored that some of the countries that I have left to visit, are in very distant corners of this Earth, like Oceania, West Africa, Central Asia, Caribbean & South America. Going back and forth is possible, but so much more expensive and time consuming.
____________________________________
Logistically, financially and personally, it makes sense that I take this 2 year leave from my 9-5 career. For those of you that think that I’ll be on holidays, think again! You cant imagine the amount of work hours I’m putting collaborating with travel brands and preparing all the logistics of being a full time traveller. It’s just a new phase on my life, my path and my career. One that makes me very happy and passionate about. 
I hope to still inspire you all to travel with your 9-5s! Love, Alvaro.

WANT TO VISIT ETHIOPIA ON THE NEXT @wanderreds ESCAPES?

____________________________________

If you’ve enjoyed all the different photogenic landmarks in my Ethiopian Series, dont miss the chance to join me on my second visit later this Year. Im preparing a tour on Mid- November, to host my second Wanderreds Escapes, this time in Ethiopia. 
____________________________________

We’ll explore these underrated spots together, discuss everything travel, and do on site workshops in photography, social media and working with brands! 
____________________________________

Dont miss this chance to travel safely, affordably and easily to this underrated region in Africa with like-minded people! DM ME FOR MORE INFO (only serious requests will be evaluated 🙏😄).

WHAT’s YOUR BIGGEST FEAR?
____________________________________

If you know me a bit, and you should by now, my biggest irrational fear are heights. The moment I look down, vertigo kicks in and my body tightens, my palms sweat and my head spins. 🙈 I still dont know how I climbed all the way up to Abune Yemata! This ancient church was carved of the rock in this karst pinnacle of the Tigray Region in Ethiopia. 
____________________________________

The best part of the story is, that a hermit priest lives there and locals still climb up every Sunday for mass!

Las Geel Rock Paintings solely justify a visit to Somaliland. They are exceptionally well preserved and second to none in terms of artistic expression with any other famous rock paintings in the World. Having the place to yourself just makes it a unique experience, and probably my favorite so far in the Horn of Africa. 
____________________________________

If this place were in Europe, or US, it would be sworm with tourists, barriers and protector screens. So, enjoy it now while it lasts! 
____________________________________

Damal Hotel and Somaliland Tours took care of us incredibly well during this daytrip and I cant recommend them enough (not sponsored, just pro-tip) (ask for Khalid).

YOU MEAN THE WORLD TO ME! 
____________________________________

If you’ve been following my Stories you know that yesterday I had a funny episode with an internet troll. I shared the convo so that we all got a laugh from a quite sad incident. What happened next completely surprised me! You guys flooded my DMs with kind and thoughtful words that came from the heart. Thats why I wanted to take a minute to appreciate those acts of selfless kindness you all had!  Sometimes in social media, we get carried away by numbers that dont matter (followers, likes, comments...), instead of the real engagements that do. Thank you for reminding me of that, and for the inspiration and purpose to continue my journey with all of you!

Do you prefer sweet or salty?

Seeing the Salt Caravans of the Afar people was one of the highlights of our trip in the Danakil with @ethiotravelandtours.

Its something truly unique to witness, as there are very few traditional commercial routes still open in the World where camels are used to transport goods/spices.

Of course, like everything, its now also become a bit of a tourist attraction. Who knows, maybe in a few years, when tourism in Ethiopia becomes more popular, they’ll stop the Caravans altogether and just set up a fixed photobooth for tourists. With only Christ the Redeemer left, I’ve seen most of the World Wonders, and plenty other non-official wonders of the World (arguably more impressive). The Rock-Hewn Churches of Labilela were up in my Wonder Bucketlist, and they were so unique they didnt disappoint.

I’m back! If you’ve been following through Stories you’ve probably seen me everywhere these last few weeks: Sao Tomé, Ethiopia, Somalia, Djibouti & Denmark! I'VE VISITED 100 COUNTRIES, BUT I ENVY THOSE WHO HAVEN'T
____________________________________

The hard part of every new place you visit, is that it won't ever be new to you again. Yes, you can always go back and revisit, but exploring won't be the same as it was the first time around. And then if you do head back, there's the eternal comparison with the memories you had. That's why I envy those with their clean slate in front of them, because they can still experience every destination for the first time!

WHERE WOULD YOU LIKE TO GET LOST?
____________________________________
For some reason, when most people think of Africa they imagine a vast dry savannah.  While that is the most popular representation of the continent in movies, truth is there are an incredible array of tropical jungles.  Some, like in Bwindi, are so deep and dense it's the only place in the World where you can find the mountain gorilla. Bwindi in Uganda, along with Virungas NP in DRC and Volcanoes NP in Rwanda, share the same unique ecosystem that should be in your bucketlists!

ARE YOU COMPETITIVE OR DO YOU PLAY WELL WITH OTHERS? (Swipe left to see these giraffes fighting #2 & playing #3)
____________________________________

As I kid, I always had the understanding that winning wasn't really winning without a loser. Thankfully, I grew up and my vision of ambition changed completely. Your success is your own, and isn't diminished by that of others, but rather is encouraged and completed by people around you.

"WHAT's YOUR WORST TRAVEL MOMENT?", is one of the most frequent questions I usually get. Of course, throughout the years there've been a few bumps in the road, but I recently had a new WORST. It was just a few minutes after this shot was taken, in these same peaceful turquoise waters. The tide that barely reached my ankles when I started to walk into the sea, quickly rose to my waist after an hour of casual wandering and photo taking. By the time I realized the peril I was in and headed back to the shore, it was too late and the water level rose quicker than I could walk through the water. With all my gear on me, and with strong currents dragging me into the deep sea, I was close to losing every valuable piece of equipment and who knows what else. After screaming for help for a few minutes, some friendly fishermen took sail and saved me just as the water level reached my chin. So thankful for their help, and I will never forget their kindness! Life lesson learnt! Be careful at sea, and never trust the tides! For more details, check my IG stories today!

node.text: I came for gorillas, but I took home one of the most spectacular Forest Walks I've ever done, thanks to @wildfrontiersuganda. Do you have a favorite forest?🌲 Backpack: @pacsafeofficial

Mountain Gorillas were high up in my wildlife viewing list! You can only enjoy this experience in three countries: Uganda, Rwanda and DRC! The latter being less accesible to tourism, and Rwanda having doubled their permit prices, made Uganda my pick! Permits are a hefty $600 for one hour with them (yes, you are guaranteed to see them!), trekking time included. Although steep, remember that those funds contribute to pay rangers, security personnel, and especially help the local communities, so they see a direct impact of tourism in their economies and are more willing to continue preserving these jungles! So, what are you waiting for! Whats your favorite animal you would like to see in the wild?

4h trekking up the Ugandan hills and we finally made it to our Mountain Gorillas. A unique experience that was up in my bucketlist and thanks to @wildfrontiersuganda and @passagetoafrica it was made possible! I fully recommend it while these creatures are still in the wild! More on the details of the experience and how to help the local conservation efforts of gorillas on my next post!

Wild Mountain Gorillas are elusive, but I didnt mind trekking longer in that amazing forest. When you are geared up and ready, you are comfortable in the most extreme conditions. Few people are allowed to have cars in the DPRK. One of the 'official' reasons being that they are very conscious about the environment. That must be a Vegan Factory!

Many of you keep asking if this and that was fake or if guided tours prevent you from seeing how DPRK really is. To this respect I'll say that although you aren't allowed to move around freely (yes, bummer), there's simply no way a whole country can be staged.

I got rid of my bucketlist a while back now. There are just too many damn good places to see.
Who said Pyongyang was all sad and grey?

Your trip to North Korea will start and end with trains (unless you are a US citizen and are forced to fly into Pyongyang). The journey is long: Beijing via Dandong, but very rewarding, as it only helps to build up the expectation. When crossing the border, just remember, dont bring any Bibles, Porn or Cameras with GPS features!

The first thing you should know about North Korea is that you need to visit with an organized tour. @lupine_travel did an amazing job with my trip and I couldnt recommend you to go with anyone else! You've all been interested by the freedom you have once you are there, and believe me, although it wasn't my usual kind of DIY trip, I had a great time!

Regardless of the season you visit Japan, it will have something unique to offer: the good Summer weather, the foliage colors in Fall, the cherry blossom in Spring or the snowy Winter! Each one is extraordinary and special! Which one would you prefer?
Golden House by a lake and surrounded by nature? No probs, Japan has got you covered!

Same same, but different. Fushimi Inari is one of my favorite temples in Japan. A bit far fetched from Kyoto's center, it's better if you visit early morning or the crowds will ruin your shots! The temple honors Inari, patron of businesses, and the trail heads all the way up the mountain between thousands of Torii (red frames). These toriies can be donations from families, individuals or even companies, and will have inscriptions on one side (yesterday's pic) and blank on the other. Which side is your favorite?
FUN FACT: This is the place where I came up with the name @wanderreds. Ok, not true, but it could've been.
Do you have a favorite forest? 🌲 🌳

One of the questions I get a lot from you guys is: "what's your favorite destination?". Well, it'd be a a tough call no doubt, but Japan would always make it to that final list of 3-4 special places. I thought it was about time I presented you my Japan travel series from my trip in 2015!
My Iran series comes to an end, and I hope I've contributed to make it just another valid travel option out there. One full of light and color. Catch the extend album on my Facebook! (Link in bio)

Sunset or sunrise?

Animals are more human sometimes than humans themselves. Take this friendship snap I took in Hluhluwe: they know what zebra bromance is all about! That's why I strongly advocate to see animals free in their habitat. And these well-run Game Reserves are a great way to preserve that wildlife! Have you been on a safari before? Where would you go, if you could just take off right now? - @heritage_tours_and_safaris

Check it out on a day tour visit if you are around, for a different setting to the "usual" African Safari! @heritage_tours_and_safaris

Still don't believe me when I say that you can travel too? Here's the nitty gritty: - Philippines: 14 days 950€.
- Iceland: 12 days 850€.
- 7 in 3: 3 days 300€.
- 6 in 8: 8 days 800€.
- Peru, Bolivia & Chile: 23 days 2200€. All these trips were in high season and in all of them I flashpacked: comfortable hotels, nice food and local flights rather than long cheap bus rides. So, technically you could even go a lot cheaper! Just pick the destination/type of trip that adjusts to your needs!

WE CAN ALL TRAVEL. I'm not rich, I don't have Dad's money or a Sugarmommy. I drive a 6 year old Toyota and live a simple life when I'm in Madrid. 
It's all about priorities. You may want a better car, or better, cooler, newer stuff. That's perfectly fine! But don't you DARE come saying that you can't afford to travel. ✌️️😜

It is surely one of the most underrated monuments out there and deserves much more attention. Get out there while it lasts!
The Golden Gate is another great example of Ukraine's capital wide array of architectural influencies. You won't be disappointed by this fortification from the 11th century!

I chose this picture because it is a good example of Vilnius' historic center. Small, narrow streets with colorful, quaint houses. The city is quiet and calm, but hardly boring or dead. It's a contained bustling energy which I feel just perfect.

Vilnius Cathedral strikes you from the moment you set eyes on it. A huge wide open square to one side and the town's hill to the other (you can even see the Fortress peaking in the background). Despite it being Roman Catholic, it is influenced by neoclassic architecture and as you can see, the bell tower is separated. 
While I sat there contemplating this landmark, it reminded me of how much more interesting it is to be different, to stand out. Not for the sake of it, just being genuinely diverse.

This river doesn't run through an unchartered forest, but through Riga's downtown. It gives the city a special allure and helps locals wind down from a hard day's work.

When you are on the road from one capital city to another, you can't help but compare them. 
Riga isn't as quaint and charming as Tallin's Old Town, but the sights have blended in better with the city, and don't give off the impression of being in an open air museum. 
Tallin was more eye-catching. However, if I had to choose a city to live in, I'd pick Riga.
Almost midnight sun in this Baltic gem. Longer days mean longer travel itineraries... So, always check sunlight hours when you are planning for a trip!!

Seagulls remind us that we are in the coast, although the huge ferries over the orange rooftops already gave it away. (Catch my 15% discount code "wanderreds2" on your @danielwellington before it expires!)

You've gotta own your mistakes. I have to say I had wrongly misjudged the Baltics! I didnt expect to find such colorful towns, live streets full of buzz, and young friendly faces everywhere! It has been a pleasant surprise to meet these gems, and Tallin surely has a lot to do with it!
Tallin's Old Town is a unique medieval haven like anything you've seen. It has a style of it's own, and believe me, you are going to love it!

Time to say goodbye to Helsinki and jump (or Ferry) on to the next stop: Tallin. 
Some people even do it as a daytrip, since it's just 2h away. But I seriously would consider doing the daytrip to Helsinki from Tallin instead!!

Any Given Sunday (Part II), you'll jump naked in a small cramped room with another 15-20 sweaty finnish dudes ranging ages 25 to 75. 
You'll find yourself on a local Public Sauna, established in 1928, barefooted, sitting your precious butt on a mouldy wooden bench that has seen God knows what. 
And you'll come to a realisation, you've just experienced another moment in your Journey that will stay on your mind forever. 
So, fuck that comfortable Spanish Summer, and Get Out There to gather some more memories.

Any given Sunday (Part 1), you get out there and take a flight from your warm Spanish Summer to a chilly Baltic Winter. 
You'll get sick of the rain, because it won't go away and it'll keep coming like in a viking nightmare. 
You'll be driven mad by sightseeing a city with no obvious sights, empty streets and mostly grey everywhere. 
But you will breathe, take a 5, and remember where was that Public Sauna your travel guide recommended.

Travelling is a game of inches, you have to get out there and be willing to fight for that inch.

My job here with the #7in3 coverage is done. I hope you've enjoyed it, but most importantly, I hope that you've seen that there aren't any time restraints that can hold up your travel goals. Get out there, no matter how little time you have, you can still cover a lot!

The Gilis are something else. Really. Once in Ubud (or anywhere else in Bali), you can easily arrange an early morning shuttle pick-up from your hotel and a fast ferry ride to this outworldly paradise! By mid day you'll be diving with the sea turtles! Here's my quick guide to pick your ideal island:

Gili Meno: the quietest of them all. Few lodging options, thus, fewer people. If you just want to be lost and go Robinson Crusoe!

Gili Air: pure comfort and relaxation. Enough bungalows and sea side bars with couches to chill all day long! Some diving clubs too!

Gili Trawangan: if you need to be surrounded by more people, and get your party fix, this is your island! The more lively and fun of all three, but maybe too loud to just totally unwind! It's the biggest and you'll find anything here!

After a few days acclimatizing in Lhasa and its' whereabouts, it's time to cross the Tibetan Plateau on to some more action!

We took on the popular Friendship Highway, 1000km road connecting Tibet and Kathmandu in Nepal. It crossed Shigatse, Gyantse, the highest lakes in the world, oh yeah, and a small mountain called Everest. 
Not bad for a roadtrip, huh? What's your favorite roadtrip?

That's me, 7 years and 10kg of muscle ago, in front of Johkang Monastery, the spiritual heart of Lhasa. I can still remember the smell of yak butter candles and incense with ongoing prayers in the background. One of those travel memories that sticks with you forever. What's your travel memory that you can't forget??
There's always that guy who wants to stand out from the crowd and shake things up with a yellow instead of the ordinary white! 😆

Getting lost in Lhasa is no big deal. 
Where wouldn't  you mind getting lost?

The first thing I thought when I saw Potala Palace up close was: 'Why haven't I heard of this place before?' This was back in 2009, when Instagram and the social media boom had yet to come, but still, I had never seen this place on TV or the news. Even now, if you take a look at popular IG travel accounts, they never show pictures of Potala or even Tibet! 
I remember feeling that this place was terribly underrated. For me, it should be one of the 7 New World Wonders. But then again, this was more like a popularity contest. Would anyone argue that the Christ Redeemer is more awesome than Potala? Or Chitzen Itza for that matter...? What are your underrated places in the world?

The 5th Dalai Lama started its construction in 1645 believing that the site was ideal as the seat of government, as it is near Drepung and Sera Monasteries and the old city of Lhasa. 
The building measures 400m x 350m and has huge stone walls averaging 4m thick. It soars 117m on top of the "Red Hill", rising more than 300m in total above the valley floor. To put it into perspective, this collossus has: 13 stories of buildings containing over 1,000 rooms, 10,000 shrines and about 200,000 statues.

Today it's Stats Day from the #roofoftheworld.😜✌️

Tibetans are arguably the most religious people in the world. Everywhere around Lhasa, you can see locals with praying beads or wheels. Devotion is a part of daily life here in the #roofoftheworld. -------------------------------------------- Thanks guys for sharing @wanderreds, liking & commenting! You are beyond cool! 👌😜
Back in the day, when I couldn't grow a full beard.

Ganden Monastery sits majestically on the side of a Holy Mountain. It was built in 1409, and this monastic complex is one of Tibet's "great three" Gelug University Monasteries of Tibet. Nowadays, it's worth the day trip from Lhasa, and the early rise to walk around the mountain for the morning prayer. After the visit, catch some Momos at the local Restaurant for a  perfect tibetan morning!

2015 is almost over, and soon New Year's Resolutions will start flowing. Travelwise, just make one: stop putting off that trip. The four main excuses out there are: 
1. TIME: even if you don't have that many vacation days, you can go a long way with 10, or even 4 days. This year, I took a small jaunt to Ireland, and it proved great!
2. NOBODY TO GO WITH: travel solo! What a better excuse to dare travel solo! You know you've always wanted to, just start off with an easier & friendlier destination. 
3. MONEY: with enough planning and advance you can find great awesome deals to cheap destinations. Try going on low season! 
4. WAITING FOR THE PERFECT TIME: maybe you are always waiting for a break to catch Spring season in Japan, but that doesn't fit your job schedule. So, just go in Summer! Dont fantasize trips, just make them a reality!

Hey guys! It’s QUIZ TIME! I’ve picked these out of the questions you sent me.Thank you all for participating!  Q: You’ve travelled to 49 countries, do you see yourself settling in for good in any of them?

A: I’ve been to a wide range of countries, loved them all. However, settling in for good is not like travelling. Personally, I’d enjoy living abroad for a couple of years, for sure, and maybe in a couple different locations, but “for good” means planting roots without a limited deadline. Things like the weather, food, customs, language, are significant barriers if you want to have a family abroad.✈️ Q: Since you often travel to remote places, do you get sick sometimes on a trip? Do you carry a First Aid Kit and what do you pack in it?

A: I used to get sicker before, when I had a tighter budget and I kept a strict diet based on the cheapest stuff I could literally find at the local street food stalls. Now that I do not travel with such constraints, I indulge myself more, so I very rarely have the occasional diarrhea. My worst experience happened in India, where I got really sick with Tifus and had a hard time getting over it! 😖 I always carry a small med-kit with pain killers, basic sowing kit, disinfectant, and meds for my stomach. In my experience, it has helped when I take these in order to protect and prevent possible imbalances caused by changes in the diet and long distance travel. I also carry now protein powder and vitamins, so I’m always keeping my nutrients on check! Like everything, practice makes perfect! 💪  Q: What is the most creepiest experience you have encountered during your travels?

A: I’ve had so many! The scariest would have to be in Tibet. We got in a pretty intense argument with our guide after he had been angry all week during a trek through the Himalayas. He and the driver pulled over, and threatened us with a knife at a certain point. We managed to keep the cool, and they eventually came to their senses. We had to cut the trip short, since things were getting a little nasty 😁. Q: If you could only visit 3 more countries, which would they be?

A: 😂😂 this is virtually impossible for me, but I'll play along: ICELAND, NZ, PERU

node.text: To get to know Ireland in depth, you need to rent a car and explore its guts. Get yourself a GPS in the deal and set it to avoid toll roads: if you love driving, you are in for a treat!! It feels to be on a rally with sharp curves and ups and downs! Some country roads even have a ridiculously high speed limit of 100km/h!! Drive safely, and enjoy!🚗

This is Kenmare, in County Kerry, one the most idillyc counties in Ireland. Small towns in Ireland are wonderful, quaint, colorful and simple in the best way. It is not surprising that almost 50% of the countries' population lives in rural areas/small towns!
Sheep don't have it that bad here. 🍀👌🇮🇪
I don't usually post about hotels, but then again, Bed and Breakfast ain't hotels! When you visit, stay in one and indulge yourself to a proper full irish/english breakfast! Tastebud heaven!
Off-the-beaten path roads & sun ☀️, what a perfect combination. Get out there and explore guys! @mhcco

Glendalough is a ancient monastic settlement founded by St Kevin in the 5th century, that grew to be powerful by the 9th century, before falling into ruin from 1398 onwards. Visit the complex early morning to have those evocative stones to yourselves! Hike up to the Upper Lake nearby for a perfect morning trip!

Who said Ireland was all green? 🍀 Arrived late last night and picked-up our car rental just before closing hours. Decided to make our way down to Glendalough from Dublin and look for BnBs there. Ended up sleeping in the car, since we arrived at 1.30am and people here have the bad habit of sleeping.😂 It wasn't that bad, and we got a chance to rise up early for a stormy dawn at Glendalough Lake. Sometimes you just need to get out there and IMPROVISE! 🇮🇪@tourismireland

Hi, my name is @wanderreds and I'm an addict. 😞 I'm addicted to Temples!! What's your travel addiction?

Thought I'd use today's post to tell you guys a little about myself: 
1. My name is Alvaro (Wander is just an alias 😂).
2. Reds comes from my family name in spanish, and most usual nickname from my friends.
3. I'm 27.
4. I'm Spanish.
5. I now live in Madrid, but have studied and lived in France and U.S. during college.
6. I DO have a 9 to 5 job! I work in Finance for an oil and gas company.
7. I travel every day I'm not working: on holidays, long weekends, summer vacation, Xmas, Easter... YOU name it!
8. I have been to 48 countries so far, some of them several times, and plan to see all 196 of them!
9. My favorite: TIBET. 
10. The country I most want to visit: Iceland!

Where do YOU want to go the most?

Sometimes things just look better in black. 
#wanderreds #diytravel #thai #buddhism

Wat Chedi Luang is a Buddhist Temple in Chiang Mai. It was constructed in te 14th century, and rose up to 82m making it the highest building in the region. Centuries later it collapsed after an earthquake, and it wasn't until 1990 that it was reconstructed thanks to the UNESCO and Japanese financiation. Hurrah for Japan!! #wanderreds #diytravel #chediluang #chiangmai

The inside of a Thai Buddhist Temple doesn't change much from one to another. And I'm perfectly fine with that. 
#wanderreds #diytravel #buddhism #thai

When in Thailand, don't you go spending all your days in the beach! There's much more to it! Head north to Chiang Mai, the cultural capital, and prepare to feast your eyes with marvellous buddhist temples! 
#wanderreds #diytravel #chiangmai #thai

Railay Beach in Krabi is a top destination for any rockclimbers or just the alternative beach troupe. The karst formations in this area are a natural wonder, and you can tour them by longboat. If you hit Thailand in summer, it's also a good beach option to avoid the rain!

#wanderreds #diytravel #krabi #thai

Thailand is no off the beaten path wonder. We've all heard about its great sandy beaches with turquoise waters. That right there is the problem! It's so crowded on high season it's no longer a secret! So if you are planning to head out there, avoid those busy months and look for a quiet week away on low season! It really makes all the difference! Have you ever been to Thailand? Tag a friend you'd want to go there with!

#wanderreds #diytravel #kohphiphi #thai

Winter is starting to make its appearance here in Europe, so I can't help reminiscing about my summer in Thailand in 2014! Thought it would be a nice contrast with next week's trip to Ireland! By the way, this shot was taken from the Viewpoint in Koh Phi Phi, you'll need to walk up a staired hill for half an hour, but the view is definitely worth it!

#wanderreds #diytravel #kohphiphi #thai #summer14

Back to Madrid! Finished with our trip! Caucasus was such a great surprise: never thought there could be so much culture to see, raw outdoors waiting to be explored, and fascinating people to meet! You know I definitely urge you to travel anywhere, but this region would be one of my top picks for a great value option for a 10-15 day trip! Always travel smart, and pick your trip not where you want to go, but where there's a better value! However, keep te Caucasus under your radar! 😉✈️ #wanderreds #diytravel #Caucasus #theend #mhcco

node.text: Hagia Sophia was constructed as a greek orthodox church, passed on to be a catholic church, then orthodox once again, moved on to become a mosque in 1453, and finally, the museum that it is today. Definitely an ever changing construction, as you can tell from its interiors! I prefer it from the inside than the outside! Don't you!? #wanderreds #diytravel #hagiasophia #istanbul
Check your bucketlist. Is Hagia Sophia on there? No? Put it right away. Yes? You are on the right track. Already been? - How did you like it?! #wanderreds #diytravel #istanbul #hagiasophia

Galata Tower is one of Istanbul's famous landmarks. Originally, it was used as a defensive stronghold from where to easily sight enemy ships approaching. You can go up to enjoy those spectacular views, but I just couldn't handle that long queue to get in this time around!! 😂😂 My advice is to get there early and avoid the crowds (not like me!) #wanderreds #diytravel #istanbul #galata

Oh, Istanbul, how I've missed you! You sure are looking good, years have treated you well!

#wanderreds #diytravel #istanbul #mosque

One last day-trip in our georgian journey before we head off to Istanbul tomorrow. Mtskheta is an enchanting town just 30km outside of Tbilisi. A short and cheap ride in bus will get you here, to Georgia's religious capital. The city is surrounded by rivers and hills, all conquered by orthodox churches. Speaking of which, you must be fed up of my church pictures by now, so I promise this is the last one for a while! 😂😂😂 #wanderreds #diytravel #mtskheta #cathedral #georgia

A bit of calm in this uneasy weekend. Just a simple, unknown church in Tbilisi Georgia. This city amazes you at every turn. 
#wanderreds #diytravel #tbilisi

#wanderreds #diytravel #tbilisi #cathedral #texting

#wanderreds #diytravel #narikala #tbilisi

Oh! Hey there, gorgeous! We're back in Georgia again, enjoying its wonderful capital for a couple more days! 
#wanderreds #diytravel #tbilisi #georgia

Baku is a city of Old and New. A city where multiple cultures blend into one colorful palette of peoples and traditions. This country feels like no other, it's not Asia, nor Europe. You just have to see Azerbaijan for yourself! 
#wanderreds #diytravel #baku #azerbaijan

This is what I call 'to be open for business'. We should all benchmark the fuck out of this store in Baku. 
#wanderreds #diytravel #store #baku #azerbaijan

The walled city of Baku represents an outstanding and bizarre example of architectural influences from Zoroastrian, Sassanian, Arabic, Persian, Ottoman and Russian cultures. It still preserves much of the original 12th-century defensive walls, which define the character of the Old City. 
#wanderreds #diytravel #oldcity #baku
What's cooking doc? 🔥🔥🔥 It's starting to get cold here in Azerbaijan, so Yanar Dag is actually very convenient this time of year! 🇦🇿🇦🇿 #wanderreds #diytravel #yanardag #fire #baku

Yanar Dag, or "Burning Mountain". You may not know this, but Azerbaijan is known as "the Land of Fire". Baku is rich on natural gas and oil resources, and Yanar Dag is just proof of it. It is said that a shepherd lit on fire by accident this natural seep of gas in the 50's, and its been flaming ever since! Its not like the "Gates of Hell" in Turkmenistan, but it's still pretty cool! Do you know of other places like these? 
#wanderreds #diytravel #yanardag #azerbaijan

Baku's Maiden Tower is a national icon. It was built in the 12th-century and was registered as a UNESCO World Heritage site in 2000. In the early 20th-century, it was much closer to the shore of the Caspian sea, but it has receded over the decades! 
#wanderreds #diytravel #maidentower #baku

Hey guys! I made it to Baku, capital of Azerbaijan, my 48th country! I'm excited to explore and wander through the Old City, and tell you all about it! 
#wanderreds #diytravel #baku #azerbaijan #aroundazerbaijan

Clouds and rain on our visit to Khor Virap ruined our view of biblical Mt. Ararat. Sometimes the weather isn't on your side. You just can't do anything about that, but get out there and keep exploring! @mhcco 
#wanderreds #diytravel #khorvirap #armenia #mhcco

King Trdat III of Armenia imprisoned St Gregory the Illuminator here, in Khor Virap. He later switched alliances to tap into Armenia's growing Christian comunity and converted himself, and thus, made Armenia the first Christian country in history (301 A.D.). St Gregory became the first Catholicos of the Armenian Apostolic Church, and set about building churches on top of pagan temples. 
#wanderreds #diytravel #khorvirap #armenia

What we couldn't see today was Mount Ararat, the famous 5165m colossus that normally appears in the background. What a total shame!! 😔😩 #wanderreds #diytravel #khorvirap #armenia

Garni is a Hellenic Temple east of Yerevan. It was built in the 1st century by Armenian King Trdat I, and soon became a summer house for the Armenian royalty after the Christian conversion. No wonder, since the surroundings couldn't be more beautiful: lush forests, deep valleys and rock cliffs on 3 sides of the temple. To get here, negotiate a taxi along with other stops in Yerevan's whereabouts, such as Geghard, Echmiadzin and Zvarnots. 
#wanderreds #diytravel #garnitemple #armenia

After a tedious commute by marshutka and a night train, we made it into Armenia!! My country number 47!! Shoutout to those customs border officers waking us up at 3am! No time to catch a rest, since we took a taxi to explore some places around Yerevan!! The lower Caucasus is still awesome here though... #wanderreds #diytravel #yerevan #garnitemple

14th-century Gergeti Holy Trinity Church is a sacred symbol for Georgia. In times of danger the treasures from Mtskheta (country's religious capital) were kept up here, in this isolated perch at 2200m. The priest there, featured in the picture, sure takes it seriously and wasn't happy with me for taking this shot!

#wanderreds #diytravel #gergeti #georgia #orthodox

Mount Kazbek stands tall at 5047m 🗻 just in the border between Georgia and Chechenyan Russia. To the east, Dagestan and Azerbaijan. So many ethnicities and mix of cultures come together in the Caucasus, amongst these huge mountains. 
#wanderreds #diytravel #mhcco #mountkazbek #georgia @mhcco

Gergeti Trinity Church is just astonishing. You can see its perfect silhouette from practically everywhere in Kazbegi. You should definitely hike on foot up the mountains to reach it! Neglect offers from taxi drivers if you can, as it is not a hard trek, but very rewarding! We've spent a few days trekking the area, and still haven't got enough of it!

#wanderreds #diytravel #gergeti

The normal, typical shot of Kazbegi is taken from the town down below to Mount Kazbek and Gergeti Trinity Church up high, tall and all-mighty. But we don't wanna be normal, now guys, do we?

#wanderreds #diytravel #Kazbegi #gergetitrinitychurch #georgia

GET OUT THERE! I live by this motto, and in few places have I seen such wilderness untouched by tourism! We were the only foreigners there! 
#wanderreds #diytravel #getoutthereandexplore #mhcco @mhcco

In love with this place! Georgia's mountain landscapes are second to none, and a great place to wander off and get lost! Wind blew hard on our trek in Kazbegi, but I couldn't be happier! Truly in my nature here: Just me, the mountains and you guys! @mhcco

#wanderreds #diytravel #getoutandexplore #mhcco

Chillin' with our ancient russky ride, while its engine cools down! Time catches up with everything...except for mountains. 
#wanderreds #diytravel #caucasus #georgia

The Georgian Military Road from Tbilisi to Kazbegi (the northest town before the border with Russian Chechenya) is just spectacular in Fall. I recommend you do it with a private taxi or driver, so that you stop on the way to admire viewpoints and take a few quick pictures! On the return trip, you can travel by marshutka (small buses) much cheaply!

#wanderreds #diytravel #georgianmilitaryroad #georgia
The Georgian Military Road is just... ...... (Pick your adjective). Autumn is a perfect season to visit Caucasus!! #wanderreds #diytravel #georgianmilitaryroad #georgia

Ananuri Fortress was home to the dukes of Aragvi who ruled the Tergi valley from the 13th to 18th century. Its two 17th century churches are a perfect taste of georgian arquitecture! It's a must stop if you are in Tbilisi or on the Georgian Military Highway! 
#wanderreds #diytravel #Ananuri #georgia

Who else loves that jungle mode?? 🌿🌿🌿 Angkor is pretty hot all year round, and humidity there is bad shit crazy! My advice is that you plan out your stay in 6-8 little tours, so that you explore the area twice a day: early in the morning, and late in the afternoon, when the heat isnt so unbearable!! In between? Just pick a nice hotel with a pool, and take it slow, you've earned it!! #wanderreds #diytravel #flashpacking #Angkor

#wanderreds #diytravel #camel #egypt

Take a flight from Aswan to the capital, but don't hold your breath because we are not done with @egypt yet!! Spend a couple of days exploring Cairo: its' bazaars, mosques, and lively streets. Don't follow a particular tour, just blend in with the chaos and let go... #wanderreds #diytravel #Cairo

These two massive rock temples just north of the sudanese border are also know as "Nubian Monuments". They were carved out of the mountain during the reign of Ramses II in 1264 BC to commemorate his victory at the Battle of Kadesh. This is said to be the first battle in recorded history to use tactics and formations, and the biggest chariot battle ever fought with over 5000 chariots!! #wanderreds #diytravel #abusimbel #Kadesh #ramses @egypt

Cruise up or down the Nile for a few days and you'll soon shut out from any worries! Travel has this enchanting quality of being able to create an alternate reality. But then again, if it were all travel in your day to day, would you appreciate it so much? 
#wanderreds #diytravel #nubian #Nile

On the way to Aswan you should stop at Edfu. Its Egypt's second largest temple after Karnak and one of the best preserved in the country.  The Temple is dedicated to the God Horus, and was constructed during the helenistic period of 237-57 b.c. Its' walls provide vast information about egyptian language, mythology and religion from that time. 
#wanderreds #diytravel #Edfu @egypt

When you finish with Luxor Temple, The Valley of the Kings, and Queen Hatshepsut's Tomb, hop on a cruise up the Nile and cross the country like Egiptians did: by boat! On the way to Aswan, you'll find many cultural gems on the riverbanks worth a stop!

#wanderreds #diytravel #Nile @egypt

Luxor is a temple complex located in Thebes, the ancient capital of Egypt. Its construction begun under Amenhotep III, but was completed by Tutankhamen. Other great emperors such as Ramsses and Alexander the Great, continued to develop it. This temple reveals the competitive nature of Egyptian Emperors: some of the names of pharaohs were scratched out and replaced with others!
